1
00:00:12,721 --> 00:00:17,017
Sneed and Company
offer their sincerest condolences, sir,

2
00:00:17,100 --> 00:00:18,977
in this most trying hour.

3
00:00:21,104 --> 00:00:24,149
Grandmama had a good
innings, Mr Sneed.

4
00:00:24,274 --> 00:00:26,318
She was so full of life,

5
00:00:27,277 --> 00:00:28,654
I can't believe she's gone.

6
00:00:28,737 --> 00:00:30,697
Not gone, Mr Redpath, sir.

7
00:00:30,781 --> 00:00:32,533
Merely sleeping.

8
00:00:36,411 --> 00:00:38,121
May I have a moment?

9
00:00:38,205 --> 00:00:39,873
Yes, of course.

10
00:00:39,957 --> 00:00:43,627
I shall be in the next room
should you require anything.

11
00:01:04,565 --> 00:01:06,108
(CHOKING)

12
00:01:11,822 --> 00:01:14,032
Oh, no!

13
00:01:15,200 --> 00:01:16,326
No!

14
00:01:21,999 --> 00:01:23,041
Gwyneth!

15
00:01:23,125 --> 00:01:26,044
Get down here now!
We've got another one!

16
00:01:37,139 --> 00:01:39,141
(GHOULISH MOANS)

17
00:01:51,778 --> 00:01:53,280
(DOCTOR WHO THEME)

18
00:02:31,902 --> 00:02:32,944
DOCTOR: Hold that one down!

19
00:02:33,070 --> 00:02:34,154
ROSE: I'm holding
this one down!

20
00:02:34,237 --> 00:02:35,572
DOCTOR: Well,
hold them both down!

21
00:02:36,031 --> 00:02:37,032
ROSE: It's not gonna work.

22
00:02:37,115 --> 00:02:39,493
DOCTOR: Oi! I promised you
a time machine, and that's what you get.

23
00:02:39,576 --> 00:02:41,912
Now, we've seen the future,
let's have a look at the past.

24
00:02:42,037 --> 00:02:44,081
1860!
How does 1860 sound?

25
00:02:44,164 --> 00:02:45,290
ROSE: What happened in 18607

26
00:02:45,374 --> 00:02:47,959
I don't know, let's find out!
Hold on, here we go!

27
00:02:48,919 --> 00:02:50,128
(TARDIS WHOOSHING)

28
00:02:56,176 --> 00:02:57,928
Gwyneth!

29
00:02:58,762 --> 00:03:00,222
Where are you, girl?

30
00:03:01,264 --> 00:03:02,933
Gwyneth!

31
00:03:03,725 --> 00:03:06,311
-Where've you been? I was shouting.
-(HORSE NEIGHING)

32
00:03:06,645 --> 00:03:08,980
Been in the stable, sir,
breaking the ice for Samson.

33
00:03:09,398 --> 00:03:11,191
Well, get back in there
and harness him up!

34
00:03:11,775 --> 00:03:13,110
Whatever for, sir?

35
00:03:13,235 --> 00:03:15,570
The stiffs are
getting lively again.

36
00:03:15,654 --> 00:03:18,115
Mr Redpath's grandmother,
she's up and on her feet,

37
00:03:18,240 --> 00:03:21,284
and out there somewhere,
on the streets, we've got to find her.

38
00:03:21,743 --> 00:03:25,288
Mr Sneed, for shame,
how many more times? It's ungodly!

39
00:03:25,455 --> 00:03:27,457
Don't look at me
like it's my fault.

40
00:03:27,541 --> 00:03:31,628
Now, come on. Hurry up!
She was 86. She can't have got far.

41
00:03:31,712 --> 00:03:34,131
What about Mr Redpath?
Did you deal with him?

42
00:03:36,216 --> 00:03:37,801
No.

43
00:03:38,301 --> 00:03:39,469
She did.

44
00:03:40,637 --> 00:03:41,888
That's awful, sir.

45
00:03:43,473 --> 00:03:48,228
I know it's not my place, and please forgive
me for talking out of turn, sir.

46
00:03:49,438 --> 00:03:51,690
But this is getting
beyond now.

47
00:03:53,734 --> 00:03:57,779
Something terrible is happening in this
house, and we've got to get help.

48
00:03:57,863 --> 00:03:59,448
And we will.

49
00:03:59,531 --> 00:04:02,826
As soon as I get that dead old woman locked
up, and safe and sound.

50
00:04:02,909 --> 00:04:04,578
Now, stop prevaricating, girl.

51
00:04:04,661 --> 00:04:07,539
Get the hearse ready.
We're going bodysnatching.

52
00:04:09,583 --> 00:04:10,959
(TARDIS WHOOSHING)

53
00:04:22,471 --> 00:04:24,890
ROSE: Blimey!
DOCTOR: Telling me! You all right?

54
00:04:25,015 --> 00:04:27,517
Yeah, I think so.
Nothing broken.

55
00:04:27,601 --> 00:04:29,060
Did we make it? Where are we?

56
00:04:29,144 --> 00:04:30,395
I did it!
Give the man a medal.

57
00:04:30,479 --> 00:04:34,524
Earth, Naples,
December 24th, 1860.

58
00:04:35,275 --> 00:04:38,445
That's so weird.
It's Christmas.

59
00:04:39,029 --> 00:04:40,197
All yours.

60
00:04:41,907 --> 00:04:44,493
But it's like...
Think about it, though.

61
00:04:44,576 --> 00:04:49,164
Christmas, 1860,
happens once, just once,

62
00:04:49,247 --> 00:04:53,668
and then it's gone,
it's finished, it'll never happen again.

63
00:04:55,629 --> 00:04:57,839
Except for you.

64
00:04:57,923 --> 00:05:00,592
You can go back and see
days that are dead and gone.

65
00:05:00,675 --> 00:05:02,928
A hundred thousand
sunsets ago.

66
00:05:04,596 --> 00:05:06,306
No wonder
you never stay still.

67
00:05:06,515 --> 00:05:08,225
Not a bad life.

68
00:05:09,226 --> 00:05:11,353
Better with two.

69
00:05:13,814 --> 00:05:14,815
Come on then!

70
00:05:14,898 --> 00:05:16,274
Oi, oi, oi!
Where do you think you're going?

71
00:05:16,608 --> 00:05:17,734
1860.

72
00:05:17,818 --> 00:05:18,819
Go out there
dressed like that,

73
00:05:18,902 --> 00:05:20,111
you'll start a riot,
Barbarella.

74
00:05:20,237 --> 00:05:21,404
There's a wardrobe
through there,

75
00:05:21,488 --> 00:05:23,698
first left, second right,
third on the left, go straight ahead,

76
00:05:23,782 --> 00:05:26,409
under the stairs, past the bins, fifth
door on your left. Hurry up!

77
00:05:32,916 --> 00:05:35,585
Not a sign.

78
00:05:35,752 --> 00:05:37,170
Where is she?

79
00:05:37,546 --> 00:05:39,923
She's vanished
into the ether, sir. Where can she be?

80
00:05:45,262 --> 00:05:46,888
You tell me, girl.

81
00:05:47,639 --> 00:05:48,849
What do you mean?

82
00:05:48,932 --> 00:05:51,101
Gwyneth, you know full well.

83
00:05:51,184 --> 00:05:52,269
No, sir, I can't.

84
00:05:52,394 --> 00:05:54,062
Use the sight.

85
00:05:54,980 --> 00:05:56,273
It's not right, sir.

86
00:05:56,398 --> 00:05:59,484
Find the old lady
or you're dismissed.

87
00:06:00,402 --> 00:06:01,903
Now.

88
00:06:01,987 --> 00:06:04,197
Look inside, girl.

89
00:06:04,281 --> 00:06:07,409
Look deep.
Where is she?

90
00:06:12,414 --> 00:06:13,915
She's lost, sir.

91
00:06:16,042 --> 00:06:17,794
She's so alone.

92
00:06:17,878 --> 00:06:21,172
Oh, my Lord.
So many strange things in her head.

93
00:06:21,256 --> 00:06:22,424
But where?

94
00:06:23,800 --> 00:06:26,011
She is excited.

95
00:06:26,094 --> 00:06:27,429
About tonight.

96
00:06:28,597 --> 00:06:31,474
Before she passed on,
she was going to see him.

97
00:06:31,558 --> 00:06:33,685
-Who's him?
-The great man.

98
00:06:35,145 --> 00:06:39,691
All the way from London,
the great, great man.

99
00:06:41,568 --> 00:06:42,986
-(KNOCKING ON DOOR)
-Mr Dickens? Mr Dickens?

100
00:06:43,486 --> 00:06:45,822
Excuse me, sir,
Mr Dickens, this is your call.

101
00:06:48,158 --> 00:06:49,993
Are you quite well, sir?

102
00:06:50,076 --> 00:06:53,204
Splendid. Splendid. Sorry!

103
00:06:53,413 --> 00:06:54,789
Time you were on, sir.

104
00:06:54,873 --> 00:06:59,002
Absolutely.
I was just brooding...

105
00:06:59,961 --> 00:07:04,090
Christmas Eve.
Not the best of times to be alone.

106
00:07:04,174 --> 00:07:05,467
Did no one
travel with you, sir?

107
00:07:05,550 --> 00:07:07,677
No lady wife
waiting out front?

108
00:07:07,761 --> 00:07:09,095
I'm afraid not.

109
00:07:09,763 --> 00:07:11,806
You can have mine if you want.

110
00:07:11,890 --> 00:07:13,308
Oh, I wouldn't dare.

111
00:07:14,100 --> 00:07:19,272
I've, I've been rather,
let's say, clumsy, with family matters.

112
00:07:21,024 --> 00:07:24,778
Thank God I'm too old
to cause any more trouble.

113
00:07:25,612 --> 00:07:27,238
You speak as if
it's all over, sir.

114
00:07:27,364 --> 00:07:28,823
Oh, it's never over!

115
00:07:30,992 --> 00:07:33,370
On and on I go.

116
00:07:33,662 --> 00:07:36,206
The same old show.

117
00:07:36,456 --> 00:07:43,129
I'm like a ghost, condemned
to repeat myself through all eternity.

118
00:07:43,546 --> 00:07:46,383
It's never too late, sir,
you could always think up some new turns.

119
00:07:46,466 --> 00:07:48,635
No, I can't.

120
00:07:48,718 --> 00:07:51,888
Even my imagination
grows stale.

121
00:07:55,058 --> 00:07:59,729
I'm an old man,
perhaps I've thought everything I'll ever think.

122
00:08:01,022 --> 00:08:06,111
Still. The lure of
the limelight's as potent as a pipe, eh?

123
00:08:13,368 --> 00:08:15,078
On with the motley.

124
00:08:18,623 --> 00:08:20,458
(BUZZING)

125
00:08:24,921 --> 00:08:27,298
-Blimey!
-Don't laugh.

126
00:08:28,091 --> 00:08:29,259
You look beautiful.

127
00:08:31,136 --> 00:08:33,763
-Considering.
-Considering what?

128
00:08:34,264 --> 00:08:36,391
That you're human.

129
00:08:37,434 --> 00:08:39,853
I think that's a compliment.
Aren't you gonna change?

130
00:08:39,936 --> 00:08:41,938
I've changed my jumper!
Come on.

131
00:08:42,272 --> 00:08:44,816
You stay there,
you've done this before.

132
00:08:44,899 --> 00:08:46,276
This is mine.

133
00:09:07,797 --> 00:09:08,882
Ready for this?

134
00:09:10,341 --> 00:09:12,635
Here we go.
History.

135
00:09:14,637 --> 00:09:16,431
(LOUD APPLAUSE)

136
00:09:23,438 --> 00:09:24,939
(ALL CHEERING)

137
00:09:42,499 --> 00:09:44,834
(PEOPLE SINGING
CHRISTMAS CAROLS)

138
00:09:54,969 --> 00:09:56,554
She's in there, sir,
I'm certain of it.

139
00:09:57,847 --> 00:09:58,932
Right.

140
00:10:00,809 --> 00:10:02,769
(PEOPLE TALKING INDISTINCTLY)

141
00:10:07,732 --> 00:10:09,025
I got the flight a bit wrong.

142
00:10:09,109 --> 00:10:12,737
-I don't care.
-It's not 1860, it's 1869.

143
00:10:13,321 --> 00:10:15,490
-I don't care.
-And it's not Naples.

144
00:10:15,573 --> 00:10:18,118
-I don't care.
-It's Cardiff.

145
00:10:20,036 --> 00:10:21,371
Right.

146
00:10:23,248 --> 00:10:28,253
Now, it is a fact
that there was nothing particular at all

147
00:10:28,378 --> 00:10:31,339
about the knocker
on the door of this house.

148
00:10:31,422 --> 00:10:35,510
But let any man
explain to me, if he can,

149
00:10:35,593 --> 00:10:41,516
how it happened that Scrooge
having his key in the lock of the door,

150
00:10:41,599 --> 00:10:44,018
saw in the knocker,

151
00:10:44,102 --> 00:10:49,399
without it undergoing
any intermediate process of change,

152
00:10:50,316 --> 00:10:54,445
not a knocker,
but Marley's face!

153
00:10:54,529 --> 00:10:55,989
(MURMURS OF SURPRISE)

154
00:10:56,072 --> 00:10:58,074
Marley's face!

155
00:10:59,492 --> 00:11:03,746
It looked at Scrooge

156
00:11:04,247 --> 00:11:08,459
as Marley used to look.

157
00:11:08,543 --> 00:11:10,461
It looked like...

158
00:11:13,381 --> 00:11:15,842
Oh, my Lord...

159
00:11:15,925 --> 00:11:20,430
It looked like that!

160
00:11:20,930 --> 00:11:22,932
(AUDIENCE GASP)

161
00:11:23,474 --> 00:11:26,811
What phantasmagoria is this?

162
00:11:31,691 --> 00:11:34,444
(ETHEREAL SHRIEKING)

163
00:11:37,405 --> 00:11:38,865
That's more like it.

164
00:11:38,948 --> 00:11:41,034
(HIGH-PITCHED SCREAMING)

165
00:11:41,618 --> 00:11:43,953
Stay in your seats,
I, I beg you!

166
00:11:44,037 --> 00:11:47,957
It is a lantern show,
trickery!

167
00:11:50,877 --> 00:11:52,170
There she is, sir!

168
00:11:53,296 --> 00:11:54,631
I can see that!

169
00:11:56,966 --> 00:12:00,345
Whole bloomin' world
can see that!

170
00:12:00,470 --> 00:12:03,514
(POLICE WHISTLES BLOWING)

171
00:12:09,938 --> 00:12:11,147
Fantastic!

172
00:12:17,612 --> 00:12:18,696
Did you see
where it came from?

173
00:12:18,780 --> 00:12:21,157
The wag reveals
himself, does he?

174
00:12:21,491 --> 00:12:23,660
I trust you're satisfied, sir!

175
00:12:24,077 --> 00:12:25,787
Oi! Leave her alone.

176
00:12:25,870 --> 00:12:28,414
-Doctor! I'll get them.
-Be careful!

177
00:12:28,498 --> 00:12:31,626
Did it say anything?
Can it speak? I'm the Doctor, by the way.

178
00:12:32,168 --> 00:12:33,920
Doctor? You look
more like a navvy.

179
00:12:34,003 --> 00:12:35,505
What's wrong with this jumper?

180
00:12:37,090 --> 00:12:39,592
-What are you doing?
-Oh! It's a tragedy, miss.

181
00:12:39,676 --> 00:12:41,678
Don't worry yourself,
me and the master will deal with it.

182
00:12:41,761 --> 00:12:44,097
Fact is, this poor lady
has been taken with a brain fever.

183
00:12:44,180 --> 00:12:45,890
We have to get her
to the infirmary.

184
00:12:47,308 --> 00:12:49,394
She's cold. She's dead.

185
00:12:49,477 --> 00:12:51,104
Oh, my God,
what did you do to her?

186
00:12:53,022 --> 00:12:54,857
(MUFFLED SHOUTS)

187
00:13:00,989 --> 00:13:03,866
-What did you do that for?
-She's seen too much!

188
00:13:03,950 --> 00:13:05,910
Get her in the hearse! Legs!

189
00:13:06,327 --> 00:13:08,037
(PEOPLE SCREAMING)

190
00:13:10,206 --> 00:13:11,416
Gas.

191
00:13:11,499 --> 00:13:13,001
It's made of gas.

192
00:13:23,011 --> 00:13:26,431
Rose! You're not
escaping me, sir!

193
00:13:26,889 --> 00:13:28,850
What do you know about
that hob-goblin? Hmm?

194
00:13:30,727 --> 00:13:34,022
Projection on glass,
I suppose. Who put you up to it?

195
00:13:34,105 --> 00:13:35,648
Yeah, mate, not now, thanks.

196
00:13:35,732 --> 00:13:37,942
Oi! You! Follow that hearse!

197
00:13:38,026 --> 00:13:39,694
-Can't do that, sir.
-Why not?

198
00:13:39,777 --> 00:13:42,405
I'll tell you why not.
I'll give you a very good reason why not.

199
00:13:42,530 --> 00:13:44,115
Because this is my coach.

200
00:13:44,198 --> 00:13:45,700
Well, get in, then!

201
00:13:47,535 --> 00:13:48,536
Move!

202
00:13:50,538 --> 00:13:53,166
-Come on! You're losing them!
-Everything in order, Mr Dickens?

203
00:13:53,374 --> 00:13:55,460
-No, it is not!
-What did he say?

204
00:13:55,543 --> 00:13:58,171
Let me say this first.
I am not without a sense of humour...

205
00:13:58,254 --> 00:14:01,174
-Dickens? Charles Dickens?
-Yes.

206
00:14:01,257 --> 00:14:02,884
-Yes!
-The Charles Dickens?

207
00:14:02,967 --> 00:14:04,427
Should I remove
the gentleman, sir?

208
00:14:04,552 --> 00:14:06,471
Charles Dickens!
You're brilliant, you are!

209
00:14:06,596 --> 00:14:08,639
Completely 100% brilliant.
I've read them all.

210
00:14:08,765 --> 00:14:10,475
Great Expectations.
Oliver Twist...

211
00:14:10,600 --> 00:14:13,644
-What's the other one, the one with the ghost?
-Christmas Carol?

212
00:14:13,728 --> 00:14:16,939
No, the one with the trains.
The Signal-Man, that's it. Terrifying!

213
00:14:17,190 --> 00:14:18,858
The best short story
ever written!

214
00:14:18,941 --> 00:14:22,111
-You're a genius.
-Do you want me to get rid of him, sir?

215
00:14:22,278 --> 00:14:23,863
Uh, no, I think he can stay.

216
00:14:23,946 --> 00:14:26,908
Honestly, Charles...
Can I call you Charles? I'm such a big fan.

217
00:14:27,116 --> 00:14:29,160
Uh, you're a what?
A big what?

218
00:14:29,327 --> 00:14:31,204
Fan. Number one fan,
that's me!

219
00:14:31,954 --> 00:14:33,623
How exactly are you a "fan"?

220
00:14:33,748 --> 00:14:36,709
In what way do you
resemble a means of keeping oneself cool?

221
00:14:36,793 --> 00:14:39,504
No, it means fanatic.
Devoted to. Mind you, I've gotta say,

222
00:14:39,587 --> 00:14:42,215
that American bit in
Martin Chuzzlewit what's that about?

223
00:14:42,298 --> 00:14:44,717
Was that just padding or what?
I mean it's rubbish, that bit.

224
00:14:44,801 --> 00:14:46,302
I thought you said
you were my fan.

225
00:14:46,386 --> 00:14:48,513
Oh, well,
if you can't take criticism...

226
00:14:48,638 --> 00:14:50,973
Do the death of Little Nell.
It cracks me up. No! Sorry!

227
00:14:51,057 --> 00:14:52,642
Forget about that.
Come on! Faster!

228
00:14:52,809 --> 00:14:54,435
(URGING HORSES)

229
00:14:56,813 --> 00:14:58,815
Who exactly is in that hearse?

230
00:14:58,898 --> 00:15:00,900
My friend. She's only 19.
It's my fault.

231
00:15:00,983 --> 00:15:02,652
She's in my care,
and now she's in danger.

232
00:15:02,777 --> 00:15:05,238
Why are we wasting my time
talking about dry old books?

233
00:15:05,321 --> 00:15:07,532
This is much more
important. Driver!

234
00:15:07,615 --> 00:15:09,992
-Be swift! The chase is on!
-Yes, sir!

235
00:15:10,326 --> 00:15:12,537
-Attaboy, Charlie.
-Nobody calls me Charlie.

236
00:15:12,662 --> 00:15:14,580
-The ladies do.
-How do you know that?

237
00:15:14,664 --> 00:15:15,832
I told you!
I'm your number one...

238
00:15:15,915 --> 00:15:17,750
Number one fan. I know.

239
00:15:21,796 --> 00:15:23,589
The poor girl's
still alive, sir,

240
00:15:23,673 --> 00:15:25,133
what are we going to
do with her?

241
00:15:25,216 --> 00:15:26,467
I don't know!

242
00:15:26,926 --> 00:15:29,053
I didn't plan
any of this, did I?

243
00:15:29,679 --> 00:15:32,014
Is it my fault
if the dead won't stay dead?

244
00:15:32,432 --> 00:15:34,434
Then whose fault is it, sir?

245
00:15:35,351 --> 00:15:36,894
Why is this happening to us?

246
00:15:43,776 --> 00:15:45,027
(DOOR CLOSES)

247
00:15:50,199 --> 00:15:52,660
I did the Bishop
a favour once.

248
00:15:52,743 --> 00:15:54,620
Made his nephew
look like a cherub

249
00:15:54,704 --> 00:15:57,039
even though he'd been
a fortnight in the weir.

250
00:15:57,165 --> 00:16:00,793
Hey, perhaps he'll do us
an exorcism on the cheap!

251
00:16:00,877 --> 00:16:02,211
(KNOCKING ON DOOR)

252
00:16:02,712 --> 00:16:05,006
Say I'm not in.
Tell 'em we're closed.

253
00:16:05,089 --> 00:16:06,716
Just, just, get rid of 'em.

254
00:16:12,263 --> 00:16:14,682
(GHOSTLY WHISPERINGS)

255
00:16:24,734 --> 00:16:25,735
I'm sorry, sir. We're closed.

256
00:16:25,860 --> 00:16:28,571
Nonsense. Since when
did an Undertaker keep office hours?

257
00:16:28,654 --> 00:16:31,782
The dead don't die
on schedule, I demand to see your master.

258
00:16:31,866 --> 00:16:32,950
He's not in, sir.

259
00:16:33,242 --> 00:16:36,078
Don't lie to me, child,
summon the master!

260
00:16:36,954 --> 00:16:39,916
I'm awfully sorry, Mr Dickens,
but the master is indisposed.

261
00:16:40,249 --> 00:16:42,210
Having trouble with your gas?

262
00:16:43,377 --> 00:16:45,379
What the Shakespeare
is going on?

263
00:16:47,882 --> 00:16:49,133
(MOANING)

264
00:16:53,054 --> 00:16:54,055
Are you all right?

265
00:16:57,517 --> 00:17:00,186
You're kidding me, yeah?
You're just kidding.

266
00:17:00,269 --> 00:17:02,188
You are kidding me,
aren't you?

267
00:17:02,647 --> 00:17:04,106
Okay, not kidding.

268
00:17:08,611 --> 00:17:10,071
You're not allowed
inside, sir.

269
00:17:10,321 --> 00:17:12,031
There's something
inside the walls.

270
00:17:14,784 --> 00:17:15,826
(GASPS)

271
00:17:16,619 --> 00:17:18,204
The gas pipes.

272
00:17:18,287 --> 00:17:20,414
Something's living
inside the gas.

273
00:17:25,628 --> 00:17:28,381
Let me out! Open the door!

274
00:17:28,464 --> 00:17:30,800
-That's her!
-Please, let me out!

275
00:17:33,427 --> 00:17:37,056
How dare you, sir!
This is my house.

276
00:17:38,683 --> 00:17:40,017
I told you...

277
00:17:40,685 --> 00:17:43,145
Let me out,
somebody open the door!

278
00:17:46,315 --> 00:17:47,984
Open the door!

279
00:17:49,527 --> 00:17:50,611
(SCREAMING)

280
00:17:55,324 --> 00:17:56,826
I think this is my dance.

281
00:17:59,203 --> 00:18:03,124
It's a prank. Must be.
We're under some mesmeric influence.

282
00:18:03,207 --> 00:18:04,750
No we're not, the dead are walking.

283
00:18:04,834 --> 00:18:07,086
-Hi.
-Hi. Who's your friend?

284
00:18:07,169 --> 00:18:08,713
Charles Dickens.

285
00:18:09,171 --> 00:18:11,007
-Okay.
-My name's the Doctor.

286
00:18:11,132 --> 00:18:12,675
Who are you, then?
What do you want?

287
00:18:12,758 --> 00:18:15,011
Failing! Open the rift.
We're dying.

288
00:18:16,178 --> 00:18:17,263
Trapped in this form.

289
00:18:17,346 --> 00:18:20,016
Cannot sustain. Help us.

290
00:18:20,266 --> 00:18:22,351
(SHRIEKING)

291
00:18:33,529 --> 00:18:34,530
(THUDDING)

292
00:18:35,906 --> 00:18:38,367
First of all you drug me,
then you kidnap me,

293
00:18:38,492 --> 00:18:39,660
and don't think
I didn't feel your hands

294
00:18:39,744 --> 00:18:41,662
having a quick wander,
you dirty old man.

295
00:18:41,746 --> 00:18:43,497
I won't be spoken to
like this.

296
00:18:43,581 --> 00:18:45,374
Then you sent me
in a room full of zombies!

297
00:18:45,499 --> 00:18:48,628
And if that ain't enough,
you swan off and leave me to die!

298
00:18:48,711 --> 00:18:49,795
So come on, talk!

299
00:18:49,879 --> 00:18:51,714
It's not my fault,
it's this house!

300
00:18:54,216 --> 00:18:56,636
It always had a reputation.

301
00:18:56,719 --> 00:18:57,970
Haunted.

302
00:18:58,054 --> 00:19:02,058
But I never had much bother until
about three months back, and then the stiffs...

303
00:19:04,101 --> 00:19:05,895
...the, um,

304
00:19:06,020 --> 00:19:10,358
the dear departed
started getting restless.

305
00:19:10,608 --> 00:19:11,609
Tommyrot!

306
00:19:11,692 --> 00:19:13,194
You witnessed it!

307
00:19:13,402 --> 00:19:15,237
Can't keep
the beggars down, sir.

308
00:19:15,613 --> 00:19:16,947
They walk.

309
00:19:17,573 --> 00:19:20,409
And it's the queerest thing,
but they hang onto scraps...

310
00:19:20,493 --> 00:19:22,411
Two sugars, sir,
just how you like it.

311
00:19:22,912 --> 00:19:24,205
One old fellow
who used to be a sexton

312
00:19:24,288 --> 00:19:26,791
almost walked into his
own memorial service.

313
00:19:26,874 --> 00:19:29,126
Just like the old lady
going to your performance, sir,

314
00:19:29,251 --> 00:19:30,836
just as she planned.

315
00:19:30,920 --> 00:19:33,005
Morbid fancy.

316
00:19:33,089 --> 00:19:34,715
Oh, Charles, you were there.

317
00:19:34,799 --> 00:19:38,177
I saw nothing but an illusion.

318
00:19:38,511 --> 00:19:41,180
If you're going to deny it,
don't waste my time, just shut up.

319
00:19:43,849 --> 00:19:45,059
What about the gas?

320
00:19:45,434 --> 00:19:48,187
That's new, sir.
I never seen anything like that.

321
00:19:48,270 --> 00:19:50,272
Means it's getting stronger,
the rift's getting wider

322
00:19:50,356 --> 00:19:51,941
and something's
sneaking through.

323
00:19:52,024 --> 00:19:54,193
-What's the rift?
-A weak point in time and space.

324
00:19:54,276 --> 00:19:56,445
A connection between
this place and another.

325
00:19:56,570 --> 00:19:58,614
That's the cause of
ghost stories, most of the time.

326
00:19:58,906 --> 00:20:00,908
That's how I got
the house so cheap,

327
00:20:00,991 --> 00:20:03,494
stories going back
generations.

328
00:20:03,619 --> 00:20:04,954
(DOOR CLOSES)

329
00:20:05,037 --> 00:20:07,623
Echoes in the dark.
Queer songs in the air.

330
00:20:07,707 --> 00:20:11,419
And this feeling,
like a shadow

331
00:20:11,502 --> 00:20:13,421
passing over your soul.

332
00:20:14,255 --> 00:20:17,216
Mind you, truth be told,
it's been good for business,

333
00:20:17,299 --> 00:20:20,177
just what people expect from
a gloomy old trade like mine.

334
00:20:25,182 --> 00:20:27,184
(FAINT GHOSTLY WHISPERS)

335
00:20:35,401 --> 00:20:36,861
Impossible!

336
00:20:54,503 --> 00:20:56,130
Checking for strings?

337
00:20:56,213 --> 00:20:58,674
Wires... perhaps.

338
00:20:58,799 --> 00:21:01,218
There must be some
mechanism behind this fraud.

339
00:21:01,302 --> 00:21:03,053
Oh, come on, Charles.

340
00:21:03,304 --> 00:21:07,141
All right, I shouldn't have
told you to shut up. I'm sorry.

341
00:21:07,224 --> 00:21:09,310
But you've got one of
the best minds in the world.

342
00:21:09,393 --> 00:21:10,978
You saw those gas creatures.

343
00:21:11,061 --> 00:21:12,062
I cannot accept that.

344
00:21:12,188 --> 00:21:14,648
And what does
the human body do when it decomposes?

345
00:21:14,732 --> 00:21:16,692
It breaks down
and produces gas.

346
00:21:16,776 --> 00:21:18,611
Perfect home
for these gas things.

347
00:21:18,694 --> 00:21:20,696
They can slip inside
and use it as a vehicle,

348
00:21:20,780 --> 00:21:23,532
-just like your driver and his coach.
-Stop it!

349
00:21:24,200 --> 00:21:28,287
Can it be that
I have the world entirely wrong?

350
00:21:28,788 --> 00:21:30,706
Not wrong.
There's just more to learn.

351
00:21:30,790 --> 00:21:33,042
I've always
railed against the fantasists!

352
00:21:33,125 --> 00:21:35,920
Oh, I loved an illusion
as much as the next man,

353
00:21:36,003 --> 00:21:38,964
revelled in them,
but that's exactly what they were, illusions.

354
00:21:39,048 --> 00:21:42,843
The real world
is something else.

355
00:21:43,761 --> 00:21:47,139
I dedicated myself to that.
Injustices,

356
00:21:47,223 --> 00:21:49,600
the great social causes.

357
00:21:49,683 --> 00:21:52,394
I hoped that
I was a force for good.

358
00:21:53,354 --> 00:21:57,107
Now, you tell me
that the real world

359
00:21:57,191 --> 00:22:01,237
is a realm of spectres
and jack-o'lanterns.

360
00:22:02,321 --> 00:22:03,572
In which case...

361
00:22:04,114 --> 00:22:07,743
Have I wasted my
brief span here, Doctor?

362
00:22:09,328 --> 00:22:11,205
Has it all been for nothing?

363
00:22:16,418 --> 00:22:18,629
Please, miss, you shouldn't
be helping, it's not right.

364
00:22:18,754 --> 00:22:21,257
Don't be daft.
Sneed works you to death.

365
00:22:25,928 --> 00:22:27,805
How much do you get paid?

366
00:22:28,597 --> 00:22:29,932
Eight pound a year, miss.

367
00:22:30,391 --> 00:22:31,976
-How much?
-I know!

368
00:22:32,101 --> 00:22:33,644
I would've been
happy with six.

369
00:22:36,438 --> 00:22:38,858
So did you even
go to school, or what?

370
00:22:39,441 --> 00:22:42,736
Of course I did,
what do you think I am, an urchin?

371
00:22:44,238 --> 00:22:46,365
I went every Sunday,
nice and proper.

372
00:22:46,866 --> 00:22:48,284
What, once a week?

373
00:22:49,285 --> 00:22:50,953
We did sums and everything.

374
00:22:52,371 --> 00:22:55,916
To be honest,
I hated every second.

375
00:22:56,375 --> 00:22:57,626
Me, too!

376
00:23:01,797 --> 00:23:02,840
Don't tell anyone...

377
00:23:04,300 --> 00:23:07,845
But one week I didn't go
and I ran down the heath, all on my own.

378
00:23:07,928 --> 00:23:12,099
I did plenty of that. I used to go down the
shops with my mate Shareen.

379
00:23:12,725 --> 00:23:14,310
And we used to go
and look at boys.

380
00:23:16,687 --> 00:23:18,272
Well, I don't know
much about that, miss.

381
00:23:19,315 --> 00:23:21,692
Oh, come on,
times haven't changed that much.

382
00:23:22,067 --> 00:23:25,279
-I bet you've done the same.
-I don't think so, miss.

383
00:23:25,529 --> 00:23:27,907
Gwyneth, you can tell me.

384
00:23:28,490 --> 00:23:30,159
I bet you've got
your eye on someone.

385
00:23:31,994 --> 00:23:34,705
I suppose, there is one lad.

386
00:23:36,081 --> 00:23:39,501
The butcher's boy,
he comes by every Tuesday.

387
00:23:39,960 --> 00:23:42,171
Such a lovely smile on him.

388
00:23:42,254 --> 00:23:44,173
I like a nice smile.

389
00:23:44,256 --> 00:23:46,425
Good smile, nice bum.

390
00:23:46,967 --> 00:23:48,636
Well, I have never
heard the like!

391
00:23:48,844 --> 00:23:50,346
(BOTH LAUGHING)

392
00:23:50,679 --> 00:23:54,850
Ask him out. Give him a cup of
tea or something, that's a start.

393
00:23:55,851 --> 00:23:58,854
I swear, it's the
strangest thing, miss.

394
00:23:58,938 --> 00:24:01,440
You've got all the clothes
and the breeding,

395
00:24:01,523 --> 00:24:03,651
but you talk like
some sort of wild thing.

396
00:24:05,861 --> 00:24:07,363
Maybe I am.

397
00:24:08,864 --> 00:24:10,282
Maybe that's a good thing.

398
00:24:12,284 --> 00:24:14,244
You need a bit more
in your life than Mr Sneed.

399
00:24:15,329 --> 00:24:16,997
Oh, now, that's not fair.

400
00:24:17,915 --> 00:24:19,959
He's not so bad, old Sneed.

401
00:24:20,042 --> 00:24:22,294
He was very kind
to me to take me in

402
00:24:22,378 --> 00:24:24,713
because I lost
my mum and dad to the flu when I was 12.

403
00:24:24,838 --> 00:24:26,340
Oh, I'm sorry.

404
00:24:28,217 --> 00:24:31,804
Thank you, miss.
But I'll be with them again, one day.

405
00:24:31,887 --> 00:24:33,681
Sitting with them in paradise.

406
00:24:35,015 --> 00:24:37,101
I shall be so blessed.

407
00:24:37,601 --> 00:24:38,894
They're waiting for me.

408
00:24:39,561 --> 00:24:42,231
Maybe your dad's up there
waiting for you too, miss.

409
00:24:42,481 --> 00:24:43,607
Maybe.

410
00:24:45,651 --> 00:24:48,195
Um, who told you he was dead?

411
00:24:51,448 --> 00:24:53,450
I don't know,
must've been the Doctor.

412
00:24:54,743 --> 00:24:57,204
My father died years back.

413
00:24:57,287 --> 00:25:00,457
You've been thinking about
him lately. More than ever.

414
00:25:00,541 --> 00:25:02,042
Suppose so.

415
00:25:03,502 --> 00:25:04,962
How do you know all this?

416
00:25:06,296 --> 00:25:09,633
Mr Sneed says
I think too much,

417
00:25:09,758 --> 00:25:11,218
I'm all alone down here.

418
00:25:12,094 --> 00:25:14,263
I bet you've got
dozens of servants, haven't you, miss?

419
00:25:14,346 --> 00:25:16,807
No, no servants
where I'm from.

420
00:25:16,890 --> 00:25:18,600
And you've come
such a long way.

421
00:25:20,185 --> 00:25:21,395
What makes you think so?

422
00:25:24,606 --> 00:25:27,067
You're from London.

423
00:25:27,151 --> 00:25:30,446
I've seen London in drawings,
but never like that,

424
00:25:31,363 --> 00:25:34,283
all those people
rushing about.

425
00:25:34,366 --> 00:25:36,118
Half-naked, for shame.

426
00:25:38,328 --> 00:25:40,289
And the noise...

427
00:25:40,622 --> 00:25:43,500
And the metal boxes
racing past...

428
00:25:44,877 --> 00:25:47,129
And the birds
in the sky... No...

429
00:25:47,212 --> 00:25:49,465
No, they're metal as well.

430
00:25:49,840 --> 00:25:52,968
Metal birds with
people in them.

431
00:25:53,093 --> 00:25:55,179
People are flying.

432
00:25:55,304 --> 00:25:57,806
And you. You've flown so far.
Further than anyone.

433
00:25:59,141 --> 00:26:01,852
The things you've seen.

434
00:26:02,311 --> 00:26:03,645
The darkness.

435
00:26:05,147 --> 00:26:06,607
The big bad wolf.

436
00:26:09,985 --> 00:26:11,236
I'm sorry. I'm sorry, miss.

437
00:26:11,320 --> 00:26:12,446
-It's all right.
-I can't help it.

438
00:26:12,529 --> 00:26:15,074
Ever since
I was a little girl, my mam said I had the sight.

439
00:26:15,157 --> 00:26:17,618
-She told me to hide it.
-But it's getting stronger,

440
00:26:17,701 --> 00:26:19,328
more powerful. Is that right?

441
00:26:21,497 --> 00:26:22,623
All the time, sir.

442
00:26:24,541 --> 00:26:27,002
Every night,

443
00:26:27,086 --> 00:26:28,754
voices in my head.

444
00:26:28,837 --> 00:26:31,924
You grew up
on top of the rift. You're part of it.

445
00:26:32,633 --> 00:26:33,592
You're the key.

446
00:26:33,675 --> 00:26:35,677
I've tried to
make sense of it, sir.

447
00:26:36,345 --> 00:26:39,932
Consulted with
spiritualists,

448
00:26:40,015 --> 00:26:42,101
table-rappers, all sorts.

449
00:26:42,184 --> 00:26:45,020
Well, that should help.
You can show us what to do.

450
00:26:46,146 --> 00:26:47,523
What to do where, sir?

451
00:26:48,941 --> 00:26:50,484
We're going to have a seance.

452
00:26:54,404 --> 00:26:55,697
GWYNETH: This is how
Madam Mortlock

453
00:26:55,781 --> 00:26:58,408
summons those from
the Land of Mists, down in big town.

454
00:26:59,326 --> 00:27:02,955
-Come. We must all join hands.
-I can't take part in this.

455
00:27:03,038 --> 00:27:04,957
Humbug?
Come on. Open mind.

456
00:27:05,040 --> 00:27:09,253
This is precisely the sort of
cheap mummery I strive to unmask.

457
00:27:09,795 --> 00:27:11,213
Seances?

458
00:27:11,296 --> 00:27:14,424
Nothing but luminous
tambourines and a squeeze box

459
00:27:14,508 --> 00:27:18,095
concealed between
the knees. This girl knows nothing.

460
00:27:18,178 --> 00:27:21,098
Now, don't antagonise her.
I love a happy medium.

461
00:27:21,723 --> 00:27:23,475
I can't believe
you just said that.

462
00:27:24,017 --> 00:27:25,394
Come on. We might need you.

463
00:27:29,982 --> 00:27:31,066
Good man.

464
00:27:31,733 --> 00:27:34,111
Now, Gwyneth.
Reach out.

465
00:27:38,740 --> 00:27:40,075
Speak to us.

466
00:27:42,870 --> 00:27:43,912
Are you there?

467
00:27:44,746 --> 00:27:46,415
Spirits, come.

468
00:27:48,083 --> 00:27:51,086
Speak to us
that we may relieve your burden.

469
00:27:52,963 --> 00:27:54,673
(DISTANT DISTORTED VOICES)

470
00:27:55,424 --> 00:27:56,383
Can you hear that?

471
00:27:56,466 --> 00:27:59,678
Nothing can happen,
this is sheer folly.

472
00:27:59,928 --> 00:28:01,013
Look at her.

473
00:28:01,096 --> 00:28:02,472
I see them!

474
00:28:03,932 --> 00:28:05,434
I feel them!

475
00:28:12,608 --> 00:28:14,484
(GHOSTLY WHISPERS)

476
00:28:18,238 --> 00:28:19,198
What's it saying?

477
00:28:19,281 --> 00:28:20,365
It can't get through the rift.

478
00:28:20,449 --> 00:28:22,910
Gwyneth, it's not
controlling you, you're controlling it.

479
00:28:22,993 --> 00:28:25,704
-Now look deep. Allow them through.
-I can't.

480
00:28:25,787 --> 00:28:29,458
Yes, you can. Just believe it.
I have faith in you, Gwyneth.

481
00:28:30,459 --> 00:28:31,460
Make the link.

482
00:28:33,879 --> 00:28:35,255
Yes!

483
00:28:42,679 --> 00:28:44,306
Great God!

484
00:28:45,682 --> 00:28:47,768
Spirits from the other side!

485
00:28:48,310 --> 00:28:50,270
The other side
of the universe.

486
00:28:50,729 --> 00:28:52,022
GELTH: Pity us!

487
00:28:52,940 --> 00:28:54,233
Pity the Gelth!

488
00:28:54,316 --> 00:28:56,485
There is so little time.
Help us!

489
00:28:56,610 --> 00:28:59,404
-What do you want us to do?
-The rift.

490
00:28:59,488 --> 00:29:02,115
Take the girl to the rift.
Make the bridge.

491
00:29:02,199 --> 00:29:03,408
What for?

492
00:29:03,492 --> 00:29:07,537
We are so very few.
The last of our kind.

493
00:29:07,621 --> 00:29:09,998
-We face extinction!
-Why, what happened?

494
00:29:10,582 --> 00:29:13,669
Once we had
a physical form, like you.

495
00:29:13,752 --> 00:29:14,962
But then the War came.

496
00:29:15,045 --> 00:29:18,298
-War? What war?
-The Time War.

497
00:29:19,508 --> 00:29:22,094
The whole universe convulsed.

498
00:29:22,177 --> 00:29:24,763
The Time War raged.

499
00:29:24,846 --> 00:29:28,976
Invisible to smaller species
but devastating to higher forms.

500
00:29:30,269 --> 00:29:32,187
Our bodies wasted away.

501
00:29:33,897 --> 00:29:37,150
We're trapped
in this gaseous state.

502
00:29:37,442 --> 00:29:39,403
So that's why you need
the corpses.

503
00:29:39,486 --> 00:29:41,822
We want to stand tall.

504
00:29:41,905 --> 00:29:45,617
To feel the sunlight.
To live again.

505
00:29:45,701 --> 00:29:50,122
We need a physical form
and your dead are abandoned.

506
00:29:51,331 --> 00:29:53,375
They go to waste.
Give them to us.

507
00:29:53,458 --> 00:29:55,627
-But we can't.
-Why not?

508
00:29:55,711 --> 00:29:57,879
It's not...
I mean, it's not...

509
00:29:58,005 --> 00:30:00,507
Not decent? Not polite?
It could save their lives.

510
00:30:00,882 --> 00:30:05,470
Open the rift.
Let the Gelth through.

511
00:30:05,554 --> 00:30:09,141
We're dying. Help us.
Pity the Gelth!

512
00:30:13,478 --> 00:30:14,646
Gwyneth!

513
00:30:16,857 --> 00:30:18,233
All true.

514
00:30:19,026 --> 00:30:20,444
ROSE: Are you okay?

515
00:30:21,361 --> 00:30:22,738
It's all true.

516
00:30:33,915 --> 00:30:35,917
It's all right.
You just sleep.

517
00:30:36,543 --> 00:30:38,503
But my angels, miss!

518
00:30:38,587 --> 00:30:40,547
They came, didn't they?
They need me.

519
00:30:40,630 --> 00:30:43,175
They do need you, Gwyneth.
You're their only chance of survival.

520
00:30:43,258 --> 00:30:44,968
I've told you,
leave her alone.

521
00:30:45,052 --> 00:30:48,180
She's exhausted
and she's not fighting your battles.

522
00:30:48,430 --> 00:30:49,431
(SIGHS)

523
00:30:51,099 --> 00:30:52,768
Now, drink this.

524
00:30:52,851 --> 00:30:56,021
But what did you say, Doctor?
Explain it again.

525
00:30:56,355 --> 00:30:58,607
-What are they?
-Aliens.

526
00:30:59,107 --> 00:31:01,151
Like, foreigners, you mean?

527
00:31:01,234 --> 00:31:03,153
Pretty foreign, yeah.
From up there.

528
00:31:03,403 --> 00:31:04,571
-Brecon?
-Close.

529
00:31:04,654 --> 00:31:06,823
And they've been
trying to get through from Brecon to Cardiff,

530
00:31:06,948 --> 00:31:08,033
but the road's blocked.

531
00:31:08,116 --> 00:31:10,744
Only a few can get through
and even then they're weak.

532
00:31:11,119 --> 00:31:13,330
They can only test drive
the bodies for so long.

533
00:31:13,455 --> 00:31:15,624
Then they have to revert to
gas and hide in the pipes.

534
00:31:16,208 --> 00:31:17,709
Which is why
they need the girl?

535
00:31:17,793 --> 00:31:20,462
-They're not having her.
-But she can help.

536
00:31:20,879 --> 00:31:22,547
Living on the rift,
she's become part of it.

537
00:31:22,631 --> 00:31:24,591
She can open it up,
make a bridge and let them through.

538
00:31:24,758 --> 00:31:27,636
Incredible.
Ghosts that are not ghosts

539
00:31:27,761 --> 00:31:29,805
but beings from another world,

540
00:31:29,888 --> 00:31:34,476
who can only exist
in our realm by inhabiting cadavers.

541
00:31:34,976 --> 00:31:36,353
Good system. It might work.

542
00:31:38,480 --> 00:31:40,649
You can't let them run around
inside of dead people!

543
00:31:40,732 --> 00:31:42,359
Why not? It's like recycling.

544
00:31:42,651 --> 00:31:45,153
-Seriously though, you can't.
-Seriously though, I can.

545
00:31:45,362 --> 00:31:47,280
But it's just wrong!

546
00:31:47,531 --> 00:31:48,990
Those bodies were
living people.

547
00:31:49,116 --> 00:31:51,118
We should respect them,
even in death.

548
00:31:51,201 --> 00:31:52,702
Do you carry a donor card?

549
00:31:54,162 --> 00:31:55,705
-It's different, that's...
- It is different, yeah.

550
00:31:55,789 --> 00:31:58,250
It's a different morality.
Get used to it. Or go home.

551
00:32:00,752 --> 00:32:02,754
You heard what they said,
time's short.

552
00:32:02,838 --> 00:32:04,423
I can't worry about
a few corpses

553
00:32:04,506 --> 00:32:06,216
when the last of the Gelth
could be dying.

554
00:32:06,299 --> 00:32:07,843
I don't care,
they're not using her.

555
00:32:08,093 --> 00:32:09,761
Don't I get a say, miss?

556
00:32:10,429 --> 00:32:12,514
Well, yes... Look...

557
00:32:12,973 --> 00:32:14,766
You don't understand
what's going on.

558
00:32:14,850 --> 00:32:18,812
You would say that, miss,
because that's very clear inside your head,

559
00:32:18,895 --> 00:32:19,938
that you think I'm stupid.

560
00:32:20,188 --> 00:32:22,524
-That's not fair.
-It's true though.

561
00:32:23,108 --> 00:32:25,402
Things might be
very different where you're from,

562
00:32:25,527 --> 00:32:27,112
but here and now,

563
00:32:27,195 --> 00:32:29,906
I know my own mind,

564
00:32:29,990 --> 00:32:31,366
and the angels need me.

565
00:32:32,868 --> 00:32:35,287
Doctor?
What do I have to do?

566
00:32:35,370 --> 00:32:37,122
You don't have to do anything.

567
00:32:37,205 --> 00:32:40,041
They've been singing to me
since I was a child.

568
00:32:40,125 --> 00:32:44,212
Sent by my mam
on a holy mission, so tell me.

569
00:32:45,714 --> 00:32:47,257
We need to find the rift.

570
00:32:48,216 --> 00:32:51,595
This house is on a weak spot, so there must
be a spot that's weaker than any other.

571
00:32:51,678 --> 00:32:54,598
Mr Sneed, what's the weakest
part of this house?

572
00:32:55,056 --> 00:32:56,808
The place where
most of the ghosts have been seen?

573
00:32:58,018 --> 00:33:00,604
That would be the morgue.

574
00:33:01,521 --> 00:33:03,648
No chance you were going
to say gazebo, is there?

575
00:33:09,446 --> 00:33:10,864
(DOOR OPENING)

576
00:33:16,870 --> 00:33:20,081
DOCTOR: Huh!
Talk about Bleak House.

577
00:33:20,415 --> 00:33:23,293
The thing is, Doctor,
the Gelth don't succeed,

578
00:33:23,418 --> 00:33:24,377
'cause I know they don't.

579
00:33:24,461 --> 00:33:28,131
I know for a fact that
corpses weren't walking around in 1869.

580
00:33:28,215 --> 00:33:30,133
Time's in flux,
changing every second.

581
00:33:30,217 --> 00:33:32,802
Your cosy little world
can be rewritten like that.

582
00:33:32,886 --> 00:33:35,347
Nothing is safe.
Remember that. Nothing.

583
00:33:35,430 --> 00:33:39,017
Doctor, I think
the room is getting colder.

584
00:33:42,270 --> 00:33:43,438
Here they come.

585
00:33:45,815 --> 00:33:47,442
You've come to help!

586
00:33:47,567 --> 00:33:49,819
Praise the Doctor!
Praise him.

587
00:33:50,111 --> 00:33:51,530
Promise you won't hurt her.

588
00:33:51,613 --> 00:33:55,367
Hurry! Please!
So little time. Pity the Gelth!

589
00:33:56,409 --> 00:33:58,870
I'll take you somewhere else
after the transfer.

590
00:33:58,954 --> 00:34:00,872
Somewhere you can build
proper bodies.

591
00:34:01,581 --> 00:34:03,500
This isn't a permanent
solution, all right?

592
00:34:03,625 --> 00:34:06,044
My angels!
I can help them live.

593
00:34:07,420 --> 00:34:08,672
Okay, where's the weak point?

594
00:34:08,755 --> 00:34:10,840
Here, beneath the arch/

595
00:34:11,216 --> 00:34:13,134
Beneath the arch.

596
00:34:13,426 --> 00:34:15,303
You don't have to do this.

597
00:34:16,054 --> 00:34:17,222
My angels.

598
00:34:17,305 --> 00:34:20,225
Establish the bridge.
Reach out to the void. Let us through!

599
00:34:20,308 --> 00:34:21,476
Yes!

600
00:34:21,977 --> 00:34:23,478
I can see you.

601
00:34:23,979 --> 00:34:26,481
I can see you! Come!

602
00:34:26,940 --> 00:34:29,651
-Bridgehead establishing.
-Come to me.

603
00:34:30,569 --> 00:34:33,405
Come to this world.
Poor lost souls.

604
00:34:34,406 --> 00:34:36,825
It has begun!
The bridge is made.

605
00:34:38,493 --> 00:34:41,037
She has given herself
to the Gelth!

606
00:34:41,663 --> 00:34:43,582
SNEED:
Rather a lot of them, eh?

607
00:34:43,665 --> 00:34:46,876
The bridge is open.
We descend.

608
00:34:51,798 --> 00:34:54,134
The Gelth will
come through in force.

609
00:34:54,509 --> 00:34:57,095
DICKENS: You said that
you were few in number!

610
00:34:57,178 --> 00:35:00,765
A few billion!
And all of us in need of corpses!

611
00:35:04,686 --> 00:35:08,064
Now, Gwyneth,
stop this.

612
00:35:08,732 --> 00:35:10,567
Listen to your master!

613
00:35:10,650 --> 00:35:14,321
This has gone far enough.
Stop dabbling, child,

614
00:35:14,404 --> 00:35:17,449
and leave these things
alone, I beg of you.

615
00:35:17,532 --> 00:35:18,867
Mr Sneed, get back!

616
00:35:23,955 --> 00:35:25,540
(GASPING)

617
00:35:35,759 --> 00:35:37,427
I think it's going
a little bit wrong.

618
00:35:37,802 --> 00:35:40,847
I have joined the legions
of the Gelth.

619
00:35:42,223 --> 00:35:45,310
Come, march with us.

620
00:35:45,727 --> 00:35:46,936
Oh, Glory!

621
00:35:48,897 --> 00:35:53,068
We need bodies.
All of you, dead.

622
00:35:53,151 --> 00:35:55,904
The human race, dead.

623
00:35:55,987 --> 00:35:57,906
Gwyneth, stop them!
Send them back, now!

624
00:35:57,989 --> 00:35:59,741
Three more bodies!
Convert them/!

625
00:35:59,824 --> 00:36:01,618
Make them vessels
for the Gelth/

626
00:36:01,743 --> 00:36:05,038
Doctor, I can't! I'm sorry.

627
00:36:05,121 --> 00:36:08,958
This new world of yours,
it's too much for me.

628
00:36:10,502 --> 00:36:12,170
I'm so...

629
00:36:13,588 --> 00:36:15,715
Give yourself to glory.

630
00:36:15,799 --> 00:36:17,967
Sacrifice your lives
to the Gelth.

631
00:36:18,051 --> 00:36:19,844
I trusted you.
I pitied you!

632
00:36:19,928 --> 00:36:24,182
We don't want your pity!
We want this world and all its flesh.

633
00:36:24,265 --> 00:36:25,809
Not while I'm alive.

634
00:36:25,892 --> 00:36:27,727
Then live no more.

635
00:36:41,616 --> 00:36:43,034
(HORSE WHINNYING)

636
00:36:43,952 --> 00:36:45,370
(GHOSTLY SCREECHING)

637
00:36:49,416 --> 00:36:52,168
But I can't die.
Tell me I can't.

638
00:36:53,253 --> 00:36:57,090
I haven't even been born yet,
it's impossible for me to die.

639
00:36:57,465 --> 00:36:58,717
Isn't it?

640
00:36:59,676 --> 00:37:01,052
I'm sorry.

641
00:37:07,100 --> 00:37:10,770
Failing! Atmosphere hostile!

642
00:37:12,188 --> 00:37:13,314
Gas!

643
00:37:14,566 --> 00:37:15,692
The gas!

644
00:37:16,776 --> 00:37:20,238
But it's 1869,
how can I die now?

645
00:37:20,321 --> 00:37:23,742
Time isn't a straight line,
it can twist into any shape.

646
00:37:24,075 --> 00:37:26,786
You can be born
in the 20th century and die in the 19th.

647
00:37:26,870 --> 00:37:28,329
And it's all my fault.

648
00:37:28,788 --> 00:37:30,165
I brought you here.

649
00:37:32,250 --> 00:37:33,752
It's not your fault.

650
00:37:34,043 --> 00:37:36,504
-I wanted to come.
-What about me?

651
00:37:36,796 --> 00:37:39,257
I saw the fall of Troy.
World War Five.

652
00:37:39,549 --> 00:37:41,801
I pushed boxes
at the Boston Tea Party.

653
00:37:41,885 --> 00:37:44,012
Now I'm gonna die
in a dungeon,

654
00:37:44,637 --> 00:37:46,014
in Cardiff!

655
00:37:47,640 --> 00:37:49,309
And it's not just dying.

656
00:37:50,226 --> 00:37:51,811
We're gonna become
one of them.

657
00:38:02,405 --> 00:38:03,615
(COUGHING)

658
00:38:07,243 --> 00:38:08,536
We'll go down fighting, yeah?

659
00:38:08,620 --> 00:38:11,247
-Yeah. Yeah.
-Together?

660
00:38:14,250 --> 00:38:15,627
I'm so glad I met you.

661
00:38:17,086 --> 00:38:18,463
Me, too.

662
00:38:20,256 --> 00:38:24,135
Doctor! Doctor!
Turn off the flame, turn up the gas.

663
00:38:24,344 --> 00:38:26,262
Now fill the room!
All of it, now!

664
00:38:26,346 --> 00:38:28,890
-What are you doing?
-Turn it all on!

665
00:38:29,224 --> 00:38:30,809
Flood the place!

666
00:38:31,226 --> 00:38:32,644
Brilliant, gas!

667
00:38:32,769 --> 00:38:34,646
What, so we choke
to death instead?

668
00:38:35,063 --> 00:38:36,856
Am I correct, Doctor?

669
00:38:37,023 --> 00:38:39,067
These creatures are gaseous.

670
00:38:39,192 --> 00:38:41,402
Fill the room with gas,
it'll draw them out of the host.

671
00:38:41,486 --> 00:38:44,197
Suck them into the air
like poison from a wound!

672
00:38:45,907 --> 00:38:48,409
I hope...
Oh, Lord!

673
00:38:49,911 --> 00:38:53,039
I hope that this theory
will be validated soon.

674
00:38:53,122 --> 00:38:54,499
If not immediately.

675
00:38:55,083 --> 00:38:56,334
Plenty more.

676
00:38:57,836 --> 00:38:59,796
(SHRIEKING)

677
00:39:08,429 --> 00:39:09,764
It's working!

678
00:39:10,932 --> 00:39:13,142
Gwyneth, send them back.
They lied, they're not angels!

679
00:39:15,436 --> 00:39:16,479
-Liars?

680
00:39:16,938 --> 00:39:18,064
-Look at me.

681
00:39:18,606 --> 00:39:22,277
If your mother and father could look down
and see this, they'd tell you the same.

682
00:39:22,443 --> 00:39:24,863
They'd give you the strength.
Now send them back!

683
00:39:24,946 --> 00:39:27,323
-Can't breathe.
-Charles, get her out.

684
00:39:28,658 --> 00:39:30,910
I'm not leaving her.
They're too strong.

685
00:39:30,994 --> 00:39:32,370
Remember that world you saw?

686
00:39:32,453 --> 00:39:34,080
Rose's world?
All those people.

687
00:39:34,205 --> 00:39:37,375
None of it will exist unless
you send them back through the rift!

688
00:39:37,458 --> 00:39:39,711
I can't send them back.

689
00:39:41,462 --> 00:39:43,464
But I can hold them.

690
00:39:43,548 --> 00:39:45,341
Hold them in this place.
Hold them here.

691
00:39:47,552 --> 00:39:48,595
Get out.

692
00:39:50,138 --> 00:39:52,223
-You can't!
-Leave this place.

693
00:39:52,307 --> 00:39:53,391
Rose, get out, go now.

694
00:39:53,474 --> 00:39:55,810
I won't leave her while
she's still in danger. Now go!

695
00:39:57,103 --> 00:39:58,771
Come on.
Leave that to me.

696
00:40:03,526 --> 00:40:05,737
This way!
(COUGHING)

697
00:40:12,493 --> 00:40:13,703
I'm sorry.

698
00:40:17,790 --> 00:40:18,958
Thank you.

699
00:40:41,397 --> 00:40:42,607
(CRASHING)

700
00:40:53,034 --> 00:40:54,118
She didn't make it.

701
00:40:55,036 --> 00:40:57,455
I'm sorry.
She closed the rift.

702
00:40:59,248 --> 00:41:02,710
At such a cost.
The poor child.

703
00:41:02,794 --> 00:41:05,672
I did try, Rose,
but Gwyneth was already dead.

704
00:41:05,755 --> 00:41:07,507
She had been for at least
five minutes.

705
00:41:08,174 --> 00:41:09,217
What do you mean?

706
00:41:11,177 --> 00:41:13,721
I think she was dead
from the minute she stood in that arch.

707
00:41:15,348 --> 00:41:17,141
But she can't have,
she spoke to us,

708
00:41:17,225 --> 00:41:19,477
she helped us,
she saved us.

709
00:41:19,560 --> 00:41:21,270
How could she have done that?

710
00:41:21,771 --> 00:41:24,816
There are more things
in Heaven and Earth

711
00:41:24,899 --> 00:41:27,568
than are dreamt of
in your philosophy.

712
00:41:29,278 --> 00:41:31,531
Even for you, Doctor.

713
00:41:34,659 --> 00:41:36,160
She saved the world.

714
00:41:37,704 --> 00:41:40,456
A servant girl.
No one will ever know.

715
00:41:55,555 --> 00:41:59,267
Right then, Charlie boy,
I've just got to go into my, um, shed.

716
00:42:00,643 --> 00:42:01,894
Won't be long.

717
00:42:02,270 --> 00:42:03,938
What are you going to do now?

718
00:42:04,022 --> 00:42:07,817
I shall take the mail-coach
back to London, quite literally post-haste.

719
00:42:08,359 --> 00:42:10,445
This is no time for me
to be on my own.

720
00:42:10,737 --> 00:42:14,657
I shall spend Christmas
with my family and make amends to them.

721
00:42:15,491 --> 00:42:19,328
After all I've learnt tonight,
there can be nothing more vital.

722
00:42:19,454 --> 00:42:22,081
-You've cheered up.
-Exceedingly!

723
00:42:22,165 --> 00:42:25,168
(CHUCKLES) This morning,
I thought I knew everything in the world.

724
00:42:25,293 --> 00:42:27,295
Now I know
I've just started.

725
00:42:27,378 --> 00:42:31,591
All these huge
and wonderful notions, Doctor!

726
00:42:31,674 --> 00:42:34,010
I am inspired,
I must write about them!

727
00:42:34,635 --> 00:42:36,220
Do you think that's wise?

728
00:42:36,304 --> 00:42:37,972
I shall be subtle, at first.

729
00:42:38,639 --> 00:42:42,351
The Mystery Of Edwin Drood
still lacks an ending.

730
00:42:42,810 --> 00:42:46,314
Perhaps the killer
was not the boy's uncle.

731
00:42:47,106 --> 00:42:50,109
Perhaps he was
not of this earth!

732
00:42:51,569 --> 00:42:55,573
"The Mystery Of Edwin Drood
And The Blue Elementals!”

733
00:42:55,656 --> 00:42:57,909
I can spread the word,
tell the truth!

734
00:42:58,659 --> 00:42:59,660
Good luck with it.

735
00:42:59,827 --> 00:43:01,829
Nice to meet you, fantastic.

736
00:43:02,371 --> 00:43:04,707
Bye, then. And thanks.

737
00:43:06,959 --> 00:43:08,086
Oh, my dear!

738
00:43:09,337 --> 00:43:10,338
How modern.

739
00:43:11,422 --> 00:43:13,883
Thank you.
But I don't understand,

740
00:43:14,008 --> 00:43:17,053
in what way
is this goodbye?

741
00:43:18,012 --> 00:43:20,473
-Where are you going?
-You'll see. In the shed.

742
00:43:21,265 --> 00:43:24,852
Upon my soul, Doctor,
it's one riddle after another with you.

743
00:43:25,103 --> 00:43:27,897
But after
all these revelations,

744
00:43:27,980 --> 00:43:31,025
there's one mystery
you still haven't explained.

745
00:43:32,360 --> 00:43:33,903
Answer me this...

746
00:43:35,029 --> 00:43:36,030
Who are you?

747
00:43:40,034 --> 00:43:41,744
Just a friend.
Passing through.

748
00:43:42,453 --> 00:43:45,456
But you have
such knowledge of future times.

749
00:43:45,540 --> 00:43:49,043
I don't wish to impose on you
but I must ask you...

750
00:43:50,336 --> 00:43:54,882
My books, Doctor,
do they last?

751
00:43:55,383 --> 00:43:56,509
Oh, yes.

752
00:43:58,010 --> 00:43:59,178
For how long?

753
00:43:59,887 --> 00:44:00,930
Forever.

754
00:44:05,393 --> 00:44:06,519
Right.

755
00:44:06,602 --> 00:44:08,563
Shed. Come on, Rose.

756
00:44:09,147 --> 00:44:11,858
What? In the box?
Both of you?

757
00:44:12,400 --> 00:44:14,569
Down, boy.
See ya.

758
00:44:18,990 --> 00:44:22,326
Doesn't that change
history, if he writes about blue ghosts?

759
00:44:22,410 --> 00:44:23,953
In a week's time,
it's 1870.

760
00:44:24,078 --> 00:44:25,955
And that's the year
he dies. Sorry.

761
00:44:26,747 --> 00:44:28,124
He'll never get
to tell his story.

762
00:44:28,249 --> 00:44:30,835
Oh, no.
He was so nice.

763
00:44:30,918 --> 00:44:32,545
But in your time,
he was already dead.

764
00:44:32,628 --> 00:44:33,880
We've brought him
back to life

765
00:44:33,963 --> 00:44:37,341
and he's more alive now
than he's ever been. Old Charlie Boy.

766
00:44:37,425 --> 00:44:39,594
Let's give him
one last surprise.

767
00:44:40,761 --> 00:44:42,263
(TARDIS WHOOSHING)

768
00:44:56,319 --> 00:44:57,987
(LAUGHING)

769
00:45:08,039 --> 00:45:10,541
-Merry Christmas, sir.
-Merry Christmas to you!

770
00:45:11,000 --> 00:45:14,712
God bless us.
Every one.

771
00:45:27,391 --> 00:45:31,354
Big Ben destroyed as a UFO
crash lands in Central London.

772
00:45:31,562 --> 00:45:32,772
(SIRENS WAILING)

773
00:45:38,778 --> 00:45:40,446
What is it, then?
Are they invading?

774
00:45:40,529 --> 00:45:42,740
Funny way to invade,
putting the world on red alert.

775
00:45:42,823 --> 00:45:45,743
By God, I'll put this country
under marshal law if I have to.

776
00:45:48,829 --> 00:45:51,999
DOCTOR: Defence plan delta!
Come on. Move! Move!

777
00:45:54,085 --> 00:45:55,169
Clear!

778
00:45:55,503 --> 00:45:56,671
(LOUD SCREAM)

